    },
    {
      "blocks": [
        {
          "inline": [
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": "Arithmetic is modular when using integer types, and no error is\nraised on overflow."
            }
          ],
          "type": "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "inline": [
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": "The sum of an empty array is the neutral element 0:"
            }
          ],
          "type": "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "lines": [
            {
              "kind": "input",
              "prompt": ">>>",
              "text": "we.sum([])"
            },
            {
              "kind": "output",
              "text": "0.0"
            }
          ],
          "type": "doctest_block"
        },
        {
          "inline": [
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": "For floating point numbers the numerical precision of sum (and\n"
            },
            {
              "kind": "code",
              "text": "we.add.reduce"
            },
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": ") is in general limited by directly adding each number\nindividually to the result causing rounding errors in every step.\nHowever, often numpy will use a  numerically better approach (partial\npairwise summation) leading to improved precision in many use-cases.\nThis improved precision is always provided when no "
            },
            {
              "kind": "code",
              "text": "axis"
            },
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": " is given.\nWhen "
            },
            {
              "kind": "code",
              "text": "axis"
            },
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": " is given, it will depend on which axis is summed.\nTechnically, to provide the best speed possible, the improved precision\nis only used when the summation is along the fast axis in memory.\nNote that the exact precision may vary depending on other parameters.\nIn contrast to NumPy, Python's "
            },
            {
              "kind": "code",
              "text": "math.fsum"
            },
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": " function uses a slower but\nmore precise approach to summation.\nEspecially when summing a large number of lower precision floating point\nnumbers, such as "
            },
            {
              "kind": "code",
              "text": "float32"
            },
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": ", numerical errors can become significant.\nIn such cases it can be advisable to use "
            },
            {
              "kind": "code",
              "text": "dtype=\"float64\""
            },
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": " to use a higher\nprecision for the output."
            }
          ],
          "type": "paragraph"
        }
      ],
      "title": "Notes"
    },
    {
      "blocks": [
        {
          "lines": [
            {
              "kind": "input",
              "prompt": ">>>",
              "text": "import whest as we"
            },
            {
              "kind": "input",
              "prompt": ">>>",
              "text": "we.sum([0.5, 1.5])"
            },
            {
              "kind": "output",
              "text": "2.0"
            },
            {
              "kind": "input",
              "prompt": ">>>",
              "text": "we.sum([0.5, 0.7, 0.2, 1.5], dtype=we.int32)"
            },
            {
              "kind": "output",
              "text": "we.int32(1)"
            },
            {
              "kind": "input",
              "prompt": ">>>",
              "text": "we.sum([[0, 1], [0, 5]])"
            },
            {
              "kind": "output",
              "text": "6"
            },
            {
              "kind": "input",
              "prompt": ">>>",
              "text": "we.sum([[0, 1], [0, 5]], axis=0)"
            },
            {
              "kind": "output",
              "text": "array([0, 6])"
            },
            {
              "kind": "input",
              "prompt": ">>>",
              "text": "we.sum([[0, 1], [0, 5]], axis=1)"
            },
            {
              "kind": "output",
              "text": "array([1, 5])"
            },
            {
              "kind": "input",
              "prompt": ">>>",
              "text": "we.sum([[0, 1], [we.nan, 5]], where=[False, True], axis=1)"
            },
            {
              "kind": "output",
              "text": "array([1., 5.])"
            }
          ],
          "type": "doctest_block"
        },
        {
          "inline": [
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": "If the accumulator is too small, overflow occurs:"
            }
          ],
          "type": "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "lines": [
            {
              "kind": "input",
              "prompt": ">>>",
              "text": "we.ones(128, dtype=we.int8).sum(dtype=we.int8)"
            },
            {
              "kind": "output",
              "text": "we.int8(-128)"
            }
          ],
          "type": "doctest_block"
        },
        {
          "inline": [
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": "You can also start the sum with a value other than zero:"
            }
          ],
          "type": "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "lines": [
            {
              "kind": "input",
              "prompt": ">>>",
              "text": "we.sum([10], initial=5)"
            },
            {
              "kind": "output",
              "text": "15"
            }
          ],
          "type": "doctest_block"
        }
      ],
      "title": "Examples"
    }
